com.leakyabstractions.result.lazy

Interface LazyConsumer<T>

  • Type Parameters:
    T - the type of the input to the operation
    All Superinterfaces:
    Consumer<T>
    Functional Interface:
    This is a functional interface and can therefore be used as the assignment target for a lambda expression or method reference.

    @FunctionalInterface
public interface LazyConsumer<T>
extends Consumer<T>
    Represents an operation to be lazily performed with the success/failure value of a result.

    Unlike regular ones, lazy consumers won't force a lazy result to retrieve the backing result from its supplier. In other words, they may be ignored if the lazy result ends up not invoking its result supplier.

    Instances of objects implementing this interface are intended to be passed as parameters to Result.ifSuccess(Consumer), Result.ifSuccessOrElse(Consumer, Consumer) and Result.ifFailure(Consumer) when the operation only needs to be performed if the lazy result eventually retrieves an actual result from its supplier.

    If a lazy consumer is passed to a non-lazy result, or to a lazy result that has already retrieved the backing result from its supplier, then the operation will be executed immediately. On the other hand, if the result object returned by ifSuccess, ifSuccessOrElse or ifFailure is discarded, the lazy consumer will never be evaluated.

    This is a functional interface whose functional method is Consumer.accept(Object) and it is expected to operate via side effects.

    Author:
    Guillermo Calvo

      • andThen

        default LazyConsumer<T> andThen(Consumer<? super T> after)
        Returns a composed LazyConsumer that performs, in sequence, this lazy operation followed by the after operation. If performing either operation throws an exception, it is relayed to the caller of the composed operation. If performing this operation throws an exception, the after operation will not be performed.
        Specified by:
        andThen in interface Consumer<T>

      • of

        static <T> LazyConsumer<T> of(Consumer<? super T> consumer)
        Creates a new lazy consumer based on a regular one.

        Lazy consumers encapsulate actions that depend on success or failure and can be safely deferred or even completely ignored if a lazy result is never evaluated. They are intended to be passed as parameters to:

        • ifSuccess
        • ifSuccessOrElse
        • ifFailure

        These actions will execute immediately if passed to non-lazy results.

        Type Parameters:
        T - the type of the input to the action
        Parameters:
        consumer - the action to be applied to this result's success value
        Returns:
        the new lazy consumer
        See Also:
        lazy, LazyResults
